    "drye_about_founder_story_B899RM": {
      "type": "drye-about-founder-story",
      "disabled": true,
      "name": "DRYE About Founder Story",
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/URZ03767_2_-min_fb60d491-6691-423b-a449-6ba709c25859.jpg",
        "image_alt": "Wilhelm and Andrew",
        "tag_name": "Wilhelm Bäckström,",
        "tag_role": "Stockholm, Sweden — 2019",
        "eyebrow": "Not another liner.",
        "heading": "For a hundred years, this was treated medically.<em></em>\n <em class=\"dryeNEW-em\"><br> It was always physical.</em>",
        "body": "<p>You've heard \"hydration is good for skin.\" Nobody told you about <strong>overhydration.</strong> Dry, cracked, burning hands — it isn't the cream, the cold, or the glove material. Same physics as fingers pruning in a bath. Cotton saturates and sits wet. <strong>Back to square one.</strong> Softened skin lets oil and chemicals through faster. Think of it as an <strong>open door.</strong><br/><br/>Seven years of R&D with Sweden's leading textile school and one of the world's leading textile engineers. The construction is called <strong>Asymmetric Layering </strong>— a textile that routes moisture physically away from the skin. We are helping <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">healthcare</span>, <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">tradespeople</span>, and <span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">elite hockey players</span> shut that door.</p><p><strong>Stop changing the treatment. Change the environment.</strong></p>",
        "cta_text": "Read the full story →",
        "cta_url": "shopify://pages/why-drye"
      }
    },
